<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1487,1803]" pageId="13" pageNumber="416">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,266,1596,1622]" pageId="13" pageNumber="416">Notes</emphasis>
. The species has a fastigium of vertex distinctly surpassing anterior margin of eyes as an evenly broad, rounded process; humeral angles of pronotum are absent, and it belongs to 
<taxonomicName authority="Hancock, 1907" authorityName="Hancock" authorityYear="1907" box="[990,1264,1632,1658]" class="Insecta" family="Tetrigidae" genus="Epitettix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="416" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[990,1085,1632,1657]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="416">Epitettix</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Hancock, J. L." box="[1092,1264,1632,1658]" pageId="13" pageNumber="416" pagination="213 - 244" refId="ref23445" refString="Hancock, J. L. (1907) Studies of the Tetriginae (Orthoptera) in the Oxford University Museum. Transactions of the Entomological Society of London, 1907, 213 - 244, pl. 21" type="journal article" year="1907">Hancock, 1907</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, not to 
<taxonomicName authority="Zheng 1995" authorityName="Zheng" authorityYear="1995" class="Insecta" family="Tetrigidae" genus="Pseudepitettix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="416" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="416">Pseudepitettix</emphasis>
Zheng 1995
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Deng" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Zheng &amp; Jiang" baseAuthorityYear="1994" box="[388,636,1668,1693]" class="Insecta" family="Tetrigidae" genus="Epitettix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="416" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guangxiensis">
<emphasis box="[388,636,1668,1693]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="416">Epitettix guangxiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is easy to identify: the body is smooth; vertex is much wider than one of the eyes; the pronotum is short, reaching two-thirds of hind femora, and the apex of the hind pronotal process is concave.
</paragraph>
